# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ice-protection-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] An **actuator** is a component of a machine that produces force, torque, or displacement, when an electrical, pneumatic or hydraulic input is supplied to it in a system (called an **actuating system**).
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The effect is usually produced in a controlled way.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] An actuator translates a stimulus such as an input signal into the required form of mechanical energy.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] An actuator requires a control device (which provides control signal) and a source of energy.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The control signal is relatively low in energy and may be voltage, electric current, pneumatic, or hydraulic fluid pressure, or even human power.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] In the electric, hydraulic, and pneumatic sense, it is a form of automation or automatic control.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The displacement achieved is commonly linear or rotational, as exemplified by linear motors and rotary motors, respectively.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Rotary motion is more natural for small machines making large displacements.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] By means of a leadscrew, ball screw, or roller screw, rotary motion can be adapted to function as a linear actuator (which produces a linear motion, but is not a linear motor).
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Another broad classification of actuators separates them into two types: incremental-drive actuators and continuous-drive actuators.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Stepper motors are one type of incremental-drive actuators.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Examples of continuous-drive actuators include DC torque motors, induction motors, hydraulic and pneumatic motors, and piston-cylinder drives (rams).
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] An actuator can be just a mechanism that is directly driven by the motions or forces of other parts of the system.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] An example is the camshafts that drive the intake and exhaust valves in internal combustion engines, driven by the engine itself.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Another example is the mechanism that strikes the hours in a traditional grandfather clock or cuckoo clock.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] A hydraulic actuator typically uses the pressure of a liquid (usually oil) to cause a piston to slide inside a hollow cylindrical tube into linear, rotary, or oscillatory motion.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] In a *single acting* actuator the fluid pressure is applied to just one side of the piston, so that it applies useful force in only one direction.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The opposite motion may be affected by a spring, by gravity, or by other forces present in the system.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] In a *double acting* actuator, the return stroke is driven by fluid pressure applied to the opposite side of the piston.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Since liquids are nearly impossible to compress, a hydraulic actuator can exert a large force.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The drawback of this approach is its limited acceleration.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] They respond quickly to input changes, have little inertia, can operate continuously over a relatively large working range, and can hold their position without any significant energy input.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] A hydraulic actuator can be used to displace the rack of a rack and pinion mechanism, causing the pinion to turn.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] This arrangement is used, for example, to operate valves in pipelines and other industrial fluid transport installations.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] A pneumatic actuator is similar to a hydraulic one but uses a gas (usually air) instead of a liquid.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Compared to hydraulic actuators, pneumatic ones are less complicated because they do not need pipes for the return and recycling of the working fluid.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] On the other hand, they still need external infrastructure such as compressors, reservoirs, filters, and air treatment subsystems, which often makes them less convenient than electrical or electromechanical actuators.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] In the first steam engines and in all steam locomotives, steam pressure is used to drive pneumatic actuators to produce a reciprocating motion, which is converted to rotary motion by some sort of crankshaft mechanism.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Since 1960, several actuator technologies have been developed.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] An electric actuator typically uses an electric motor to generate torque, which is then converted into linear or rotary motion to drive a mechanical system.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] An electromechanical actuator (EMA) uses mechanical means to convert the rotational force of an ordinary (rotary) electric motor into a linear movement.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The mechanism may be a toothed belt or a screw (either a ball or a lead screw or planetary roller screw).
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The main advantages of electromechanical actuators are their relatively good level of accuracy with respect to pneumatics, their possible long lifecycle and the little maintenance effort required (might require grease).
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] It is possible to reach relatively high force, on the order of 100 kN.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The main limitation of these actuators are the reachable speed, the important dimensions and weight they require.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The main application of such actuators is mainly seen in health care devices and factory automation.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Another approach is an electrohydraulic actuator, where the electric motor remains the prime mover but provides torque to operate a hydraulic accumulator that is then used to transmit actuation force in much the same way that diesel engine/hydraulics are typically used in heavy equipment.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Electrical energy is used to actuate equipment such as multi-turn valves, or electric-powered construction and excavation equipment.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] When used to control the flow of fluid through a valve, a brake is typically installed above the motor to prevent the fluid pressure from forcing open the valve.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] If no brake is installed, the actuator gets activated to reclose the valve, which is slowly forced open again.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] This sets up an oscillation (open, close, open ...) and the motor and actuator will eventually become damaged.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Electric rotary actuators use a rotary motor to turn the target part over a certain angle.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Rotary actuators can have up to a rotation of 360 degrees.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] This allows it to differ from a linear motor as the linear is bound to a set distance compared to the rotary motor.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Rotary motors have the ability to be set at any given degree in a field making the device easier to set up still with durability and a set torque.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Rotary motors can be powered by 3 different techniques such as Electric, Fluid, or Manual.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] However, Fluid powered rotary actuators have 5 sub-sections of actuators such as Scotch Yoke, Vane, Rack-and-Pinion, Helical, and Electrohydraulic.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] All forms have their own specific design and use allowing the ability to choose multiple angles of degree.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Rotary actuators have numerous applications but are often found in hydraulic pressured devices and industries or tasks with motion control systems.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Rotary actuators are even used in robotic arms in industry lines.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] A linear electric actuator uses a linear motor, which can be thought as a rotary electric motor which has been cut and unrolled.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Thus, instead of producing a rotational movement, it produces a linear force along their length.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Because it generally has lower friction losses than the alternatives, a linear electric actuator can last over a hundred million cycles.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Linear motors are divided in 3 basic categories: flat linear motor (classic), U-Channel linear motors and Tubular linear motors.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Linear motor technology is the best solution in the context of a low load (up to 30Kg) because it provides the highest level of speed, control and accuracy.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] In fact, it represents the most desired and versatile technology.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Due to the limitations of pneumatics, the current electric actuator technology is a viable solution for specific industry applications and it has been successfully introduced in market segments such as the watchmaking, semiconductor and pharmaceutical industries (as high as 60% of the applications.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] An actuator may be driven by heat through the expansion that most solid material exhibit when the temperature increases.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] This principle is commonly used, for example, to operate electric switches in thermostats.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Typically, a (non-electronic) thermostat contains a strip with two layers of different metals, that will bend when heated.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Thermal actuators may also exploit the properties of shape-memory alloys.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Some actuators are driven by externally applied magnetic fields.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] They typically contain parts made of ferromagnetic materials that are strongly attracted to each other when they are magnetized by the external field.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] An example are the reed switches that may be used as door opening sensors in a building security system.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Alternatively, magnetic actuators can use magnetic shape-memory alloys.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] A soft actuator is made of a flexible material that changes its shape in response to stimuli including mechanical, thermal, magnetic, and electrical.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Soft actuators mainly deal with the robotics of humans rather than industry which is what most of the actuators are used for.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] For most actuators they are mechanically durable yet do not have an ability to adapt compared to soft actuators.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The soft actuators apply to mainly safety and healthcare for humans which is why they are able to adapt to environments by disassembling their parts.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated using multistep low yield processes such as micro-moulding, solid freeform fabrication, and mask lithography.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] However, these methods require manual fabrication of devices, post processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until maturity in the fabrication is achieved.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] To avoid the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Therefore, special soft systems that can be fabricated in a single step by rapid prototyping methods, such as 3D printing, are utilized to narrow the gap between the design and implementation of soft actuators, making the process faster, less expensive, and simpler.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Shape memory polymer (SMP) actuators are the most similar to our muscles, providing a response to a range of stimuli such as light, electrical, magnetic, heat, pH, and moisture changes.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] They have some deficiencies including fatigue and high response time that have been improved through the introduction of smart materials and combination of different materials by means of advanced fabrication technology.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The advent of 3D printers has made a new pathway for fabricating low-cost and fast response SMP actuators.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The process of receiving external stimuli like heat, moisture, electrical input, light or magnetic field by SMP is referred to as shape memory effect (SME).
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] SMP exhibits some rewarding features such a low density, high strain recovery, biocompatibility, and biodegradability.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Photopolymers or light activated polymers (LAP) are another type of SMP that are activated by light stimuli.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The LAP actuators can be controlled remotely with instant response and, without any physical contact, only with the variation of light frequency or intensity.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] A need for soft, lightweight and biocompatible soft actuators in soft robotics has influenced researchers for devising pneumatic soft actuators because of their intrinsic compliance nature and ability to produce muscle tension.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Polymers such as dielectric elastomers (DE), ionic polymer–metal composites (IPMC), ionic electroactive polymers, polyelectrolyte gels, and gel-metal composites are common materials to form 3D layered structures that can be tailored to work as soft actuators.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] EAP actuators are categorized as 3D printed soft actuators that respond to electrical excitation as deformation in their shape.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] In engineering, actuators are frequently used as mechanisms to introduce motion, or to clamp an object so as to prevent motion.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] In electronic engineering, actuators are a subdivision of transducers.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] They are devices which transform an input signal (mainly an electrical signal) into some form of motion.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Rotary motors are primarily used when rotational motion is required, but can also be used for linear applications by transforming rotary motion into linear motion with a lead screw or similar mechanism.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] On the other hand, some actuators are intrinsically linear, such as piezoelectric actuators.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] In virtual instrumentation, actuators and sensors are the hardware complements of virtual instruments.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Performance metrics for actuators include speed, acceleration, and force (alternatively, angular speed, angular acceleration, and torque), as well as energy efficiency and considerations such as mass, volume, operating conditions, and durability, among others.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] When considering force in actuators for applications, two main metrics should be considered.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Static load is the force capability of the actuator while not in motion.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Conversely, the dynamic load of the actuator is the force capability while in motion.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Speed should be considered primarily at a no-load pace, since the speed will invariably decrease as the load amount increases.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] The rate the speed will decrease will directly correlate with the amount of force and the initial speed.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Actuators are commonly rated using the standard IP Code rating system.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] Those that are rated for dangerous environments will have a higher IP rating than those for personal or common industrial use.
[src:ice-protection-system/actuators] This will be determined by each individual manufacturer, depending on usage and quality.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] An **adaptive compliant wing** is a wing which is flexible enough for aspects of its shape to be changed in flight.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible wings have a number of benefits.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] Conventional flight control mechanisms operate using hinges, resulting in disruptions to the airflow, vortices, and in some cases, separation of the airflow.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] These effects contribute to the drag of the aircraft, resulting in less efficiency and higher fuel costs.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible aerofoils can manipulate aerodynamic forces with less disruptions to the flow, resulting in less aerodynamic drag and improved fuel economy.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changing the shape of an aerodynamic surface has a direct effect on its aerodynamic properties.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] According to the flow condition and to the initial shape of the part, each shape variation (curvature, incidence, twist...) can have a different impact on the resulting forces and moments.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] This characteristic is actively pursued in adaptive wings which – by nature of their distributed compliance – can attain shape changes in a continuous, smooth, gap-free manner.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] By altering these geometrical parameters, the forces and moments can be modified, permitting to tailor them to the specific flight condition (e.g. for drag reduction) or to perform maneuvers (e.g. roll).
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] Shape adaptation can be classified according to the motion it enables.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changes of the airfoil shapes include altering its twist, and changing its camber and thickness distribution.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] An adaptive compliant wing designed by FlexSys Inc. features a variable-camber trailing edge which can be deflected up to ±10°, thus acting like a flap-equipped wing, but without the individual segments and gaps typical in a flap system.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing itself can be twisted up to 1° per foot of span.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing's shape can be changed at a rate of 30° per second, which is ideal for gust load alleviation.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] The development of the adaptive compliant wing is being sponsored by the U.S.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] Initially, the wing was tested in a wind tunnel, and then a 50-inch (1.3 m) section of wing was flight tested on board the Scaled Composites White Knight research aircraft in a seven-flight, 20-hour program operated from the Mojave Spaceport.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] Adaptive compliant wings are also investigated at ETH Zurich in the frame of the Smart airfoil project.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] The EU-funded Flexop program aims to develop to enable higher wing aspect ratio for less induced drag with lighter, more flexible airliner wings, along developing active flutter suppression for flexible wings.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] Partners include Hungary's MTA SZTAKI, Airbus, Austria's FACC, Inasco of Greece, Delft University of Technology, German aerospace center DLR, TUM, the UK's University of Bristol and RWTH Aachen University in Germany.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] On 19 November 2019, a 7 m (23 ft) span jet-powered UAV demonstrator with an aeroelastically tailored wing for passive load alleviation was flown in Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany, previously flown with a carbon-fiber, rigid wing to establish baseline performance.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] It has a conventional tube-and-wing configuration, unlike the blended wing body of the Lockheed Martin X-56.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] It follows the Grumman X-29 demonstrator in 1984, with more refined fiber orientations.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] The flexible wing is 4% lighter than the rigid one.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] The 54-month, €6.67 million ($7.4 million) project ends in November 2019, followed by the €3.85 million FLiPASED program from September 2019 until December 2022, using all the movable surfaces.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] The glass fiber flutter wing should to be flown in 2020, with unstable aeroelastic modes under 55 m/s (107 kn) that must be actively suppressed.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] With optimized aeroelastic tailoring and active flutter suppression, an aspect ratio of 12.4 could reduce fuel-burn by 5%, and 7% are targeted.
[src:ice-protection-system/adaptive-compliant-wing] FLiPASED is also led by MTA SZTAKI and include partners TUM, DLR and French aerospace research agency ONERA.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerodynamics] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogels are produced by extracting the liquid component of a gel through supercritical drying or freeze-drying.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] This allows the liquid to be slowly dried off without causing the solid matrix in the gel to collapse from capillary action, as would happen with conventional evaporation.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The first aerogels were produced from silica gels.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Kistler's later work involved aerogels based on alumina, chromia, and tin dioxide.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Carbon aerogels were first developed in the late 1980s.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The first documented example of an aerogel was created by Samuel Stephens Kistler in 1931, as a result of a bet with Charles Learned over who could replace the liquid in "jellies" with gas without causing shrinkage.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Despite the name, aerogels are solid, rigid, and dry materials that do not resemble a gel in their physical properties: the name is because they are made *from* gels.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Pressing softly on an aerogel typically does not leave even a minor mark; pressing more firmly will leave a permanent depression.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Pressing extremely firmly will cause a breakdown in the sparse structure causing it to shatter like glass (a property known as *friability*), although more modern variations do not suffer from this.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Even though it is prone to shattering, it is very strong structurally.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Its impressive load-bearing abilities are due to the dendritic microstructure in which spherical particles of average size 2–5 nm are fused together into clusters.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] These clusters form a three-dimensional highly porous structure of almost fractal chains, with pores just under 100 nm.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The average size and density of the pores can be controlled during the manufacturing process.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] An aerogel material can range from 50% to 99.98% air by volume, but in practice most aerogels exhibit somewhere between 90 and 99.8% porosity.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogels have a porous solid network that contains air pockets, with the air pockets taking up the majority of space within the material.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogels are good thermal insulators because they almost nullify two of the three methods of heat transfer – conduction (they are mostly composed of insulating gas) and convection (the microstructure prevents net gas movement).
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] They are good conductive insulators because they are composed almost entirely of gases, which are very poor heat conductors.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] (Silica aerogel is an especially good insulator because silica is also a poor conductor of heat; a metallic or carbon aerogel, on the other hand, would be less effective.) They are good convective inhibitors because air cannot circulate through the lattice.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogels are poor radiative insulators because infrared radiation (which transfers heat) passes through them.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Owing to its hygroscopic nature, aerogel feels dry and acts as a strong desiccant.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] People handling aerogel for extended periods should wear gloves to prevent the appearance of dry brittle spots on their skin.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The slight color it does have is due to Rayleigh scattering of the shorter wavelengths of visible light by the nano-sized dendritic structure.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] This causes it to appear smoky blue against dark backgrounds and yellowish against bright backgrounds.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogels by themselves are hydrophilic, and if they absorb moisture they usually suffer a structural change, such as contraction, and deteriorate, but degradation can be prevented by making them hydrophobic, via a chemical treatment.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogels with hydrophobic interiors are less susceptible to degradation than aerogels with only an outer hydrophobic layer, especially if a crack penetrates the surface.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogel structure results from a sol-gel polymerization, which is when monomers (simple molecules) react with other monomers to form a sol or a substance that consists of bonded, cross-linked macromolecules with deposits of liquid solution among them.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] When the material is critically heated, the liquid evaporates and the bonded, cross-linked macromolecule frame is left behind.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The result of the polymerization and critical heating is the creation of a material that has a porous strong structure classified as aerogel.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Variations in synthesis can alter the surface area and pore size of the aerogel.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The smaller the pore size the more susceptible the aerogel is to fracture.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] There are several ways to determine the porosity of aerogel: the three main methods are gas adsorption, mercury porosimetry, and scattering method.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] In gas adsorption, nitrogen at its boiling point is adsorbed into the aerogel sample.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The gas being adsorbed is dependent on the size of the pores within the sample and on the partial pressure of the gas relative to its saturation pressure.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The volume of the gas adsorbed is measured by using the Brunauer, Emmit and Teller formula (BET), which gives the specific surface area of the sample.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] At high partial pressure in the adsorption/desorption the Kelvin equation gives the pore size distribution of the sample.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] In mercury porosimetry, the mercury is forced into the aerogel porous system to determine the pores' size, but this method is highly inefficient since the solid frame of aerogel will collapse from the high compressive force.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The scattering method involves the angle-dependent deflection of radiation within the aerogel sample.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The sample can be solid particles or pores.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The radiation goes into the material and determines the fractal geometry of the aerogel pore network.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The best radiation wavelengths to use are X-rays and neutrons.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The high porosity and surface area of silica aerogels allow them to be used in a variety of environmental filtration applications.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogels may have a thermal conductivity smaller than that of the gas they contain.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] This is caused by the Knudsen effect, a reduction of thermal conductivity in gases when the size of the cavity encompassing the gas becomes comparable to the mean free path.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Effectively, the cavity restricts the movement of the gas particles, decreasing the thermal conductivity in addition to eliminating convection.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] For example, thermal conductivity of air is about 25 mW·m−1·K−1 at standard temperature and pressure (STP) and in a large container, but decreases to about 5 mW·m−1·K−1 in a pore 30 nanometers in diameter.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogel contains particles that are 2–5 nm in diameter.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] After the process of creating aerogel, it will contain a large amount of hydroxyl groups on the surface.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The hydroxyl groups can cause a strong reaction when the aerogel is placed in water, causing it to dissolve in the water.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] One way to waterproof the hydrophilic aerogel is by soaking the aerogel with some chemical base that will replace the surface hydroxyl groups (–OH) with non-polar groups (–O*R*), a process which is most effective when *R* is an aliphatic group.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The preparation of silica aerogels typically involves three distinct steps: the sol-gel transition (gelation), the network perfection (aging), and the gel-aerogel transition (drying).
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Silica aerogels are typically synthesized by using a sol-gel process.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The first step of the sol-gel process is the creation of a colloidal suspension of solid particles known as a "sol".
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The precursors are a liquid alcohol such as ethanol which is mixed with a silicon alkoxide, such as tetramethoxysilane (TMOS), tetraethoxysilane (TEOS), and polyethoxydisiloxane (PEDS) (earlier work used sodium silicates).
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The solution of silica is mixed with a catalyst and allowed to gel during a hydrolysis reaction which forms particles of silicon dioxide.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The oxide suspension begins to undergo condensation reactions which result in the creation of metal oxide bridges (either M–O–M, "oxo" bridges, or M–OH–M, "ol" bridges) linking the dispersed colloidal particles.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] These reactions generally have moderately slow reaction rates, and as a result either acidic or basic catalysts are used to improve the processing speed.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Basic catalysts tend to produce more transparent aerogels and minimize the shrinkage during the drying process and also strengthen it to prevent pore collapse during drying.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] For some materials, the transition from a colloidal dispersion into a gel happens without the addition of crosslinking materials.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] For others, crosslinking materials are added to the dispersion to promote the strong interaction of the solid particles in order to form the gel.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The gelation time depends heavily on a variety of factors such as the chemical composition of the precursor solution, the concentration of the precursor materials and additives, the processing temperature, and the pH.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Many materials may require additional curing after gelation (i.e., network perfection) in order to strengthen the aerogel network.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Once the gelation is completed, the liquid surrounding the silica network is carefully removed and replaced with air, while keeping the aerogel intact.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] It is crucial that the gel is dried in such a way as to minimize the surface tension within the pores of the solid network.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] This is typically accomplished through supercritical fluid extraction using supercritical carbon dioxide (scCO2) or freeze-drying.This section briefly describes and compares the processing strategies of supercritical drying and freeze-drying.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Gels where the liquid is allowed to evaporate at a natural rate are known as xerogels (i. e. are not aerogels).
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] As the liquid evaporates in such manner, forces caused by surface tensions of the liquid-solid interfaces are enough to destroy the fragile gel network.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] As a result, xerogels cannot achieve the high porosities and instead peak at lower porosities and exhibit large amounts of shrinkage after drying.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] To avoid the collapse of fibers during slow solvent evaporation and reduce surface tensions of the liquid-solid interfaces, aerogels can be formed by lyophilization (freeze-drying).
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Depending on the concentration of the fibers and the temperature to freeze the material, the properties such as porosity of the final aerogel will be affected.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] In 1931, to develop the first aerogels, Kistler used a process known as supercritical drying which avoids a direct phase change.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] By increasing the temperature and pressure he forced the liquid into a supercritical fluid state where by dropping the pressure he could instantly gasify and remove the liquid inside the aerogel, avoiding damage to the delicate three-dimensional network.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] While this can be done with ethanol, the high temperatures and pressures lead to dangerous processing conditions.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] A safer, lower temperature and pressure method involves a solvent exchange.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] This is typically done by exchanging the initial aqueous pore liquid for a CO2-miscible liquid such as ethanol or acetone, then onto liquid carbon dioxide, and then bringing the carbon dioxide above its critical point.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] A variant on this process involves the direct injection of supercritical carbon dioxide into the pressure vessel containing the aerogel.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The result of either process exchanges the initial liquid from the gel with carbon dioxide, without allowing the gel structure to collapse or lose volume.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] To dry the gel, while preserving the highly porous network of an aerogel, supercritical drying employs the use of the liquid-gas transition that occurs beyond the critical point of a substance.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] By using this liquid-gas transition that avoids crossing the liquid-gas phase boundary, the surface tension that would arise within the pores due to the evaporation of a liquid is eliminated, thereby preventing the collapse of the pores.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Through heating and pressurization, the liquid solvent reaches its critical point, at which point the liquid and gas phases become indistinguishable.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Past this point, the supercritical fluid is converted into the gaseous phase upon an isothermal de-pressurization.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] This process results in a phase change without crossing the liquid-gas phase boundary.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] This method is proven to be excellent at preserving the highly porous nature of the solid network without significant shrinkage or cracking.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] While other fluids have been reported for the creation of supercritically dried aerogels, scCO2 is the most common substance with a relatively mild supercritical point at 31 °C and 7.4 MPa.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] CO2 is also relatively non-toxic, non-flammable, inert, and cost-effective when compared to other fluids, such as methanol or ethanol.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] While being a highly effective method for producing aerogels, supercritical drying takes several days, requires specialized equipment, and presents significant safety hazards due to its high-pressure operation.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Freeze-drying, also known as freeze-casting or ice-templating, offers an alternative to the high temperature and high-pressure requirements of supercritical drying.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Additionally, freeze-drying offers more control of the solid structure development by controlling the ice crystal growth during freezing.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] In this method, a colloidal dispersion of the aerogel precursors is frozen, with the liquid component freezing into different morphologies depending on a variety of factors such as the precursor concentration, type of liquid, temperature of freezing, and freezing container.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] As this liquid freezes, the solid precursor molecules are forced into the spaces between the growing crystals.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Once completely frozen, the frozen liquid is sublimed into a gas through lyophilization, which removes much of the capillary forces, as was observed in supercritical drying.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Though typically classified as a "cryogel", aerogels produced through freeze-drying often experience some shrinkage and cracking while also producing a non-homogenous aerogel framework.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] This often leads to freeze-drying being used for the creation of aerogel powders or as a framework for composite aerogels.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Resorcinol–formaldehyde aerogel (RF aerogel) is made in a way similar to production of silica aerogel.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] A carbon aerogel can then be made from this resorcinol–formaldehyde aerogel by pyrolysis in an inert gas atmosphere, leaving a matrix of carbon.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The resulting carbon aerogel may be used to produce solid shapes, powders, or composite paper.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Additives have been successful in enhancing certain properties of the aerogel for the use of specific applications.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogel composites have been made using a variety of continuous and discontinuous reinforcements.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The high aspect ratio of fibers such as fiberglass have been used to reinforce aerogel composites with significantly improved mechanical properties.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Silica aerogels are the most common type of aerogel, and the primary type in use or study.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] It is silica-based and can be derived from silica gel or by a modified Stober process.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Nicknames include *frozen smoke*, *solid smoke*, *solid air*, *solid cloud*, and *blue smoke*, owing to its translucent nature and the way light scatters in the material.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The lowest-density silica nanofoam weighs 1,000 g/m3, which is the evacuated version of the record-aerogel of 1,900 g/m3.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The density of air is 1,200 g/m3 (at 20 °C and 1 atm).
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The silica solidifies into three-dimensional, intertwined clusters that make up only 3% of the volume.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Conduction through the solid is therefore very low.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The remaining 97% of the volume is composed of air in extremely small nanopores.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The air has little room to move, inhibiting both convection and gas-phase conduction.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Silica aerogel also has a high optical transmission of ~99% and a low refractive index of ~1.05.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] It is very robust with respect to high power input beam in continuous wave regime and does not show any boiling or melting phenomena.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] This property permits to study high intensity nonlinear waves in the presence of disorder in regimes typically unaccessible by liquid materials, making it promising material for nonlinear optics.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] This aerogel has remarkable thermal insulative properties, although its thermal conductivity depends on formulation, density, pressure and measurement method.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Until 2011, silica aerogel held 15 entries in *Guinness World Records* for material properties, including best insulator and lowest-density solid, though it was ousted from the latter title by the even lighter materials aerographite in 2012 and then aerographene in 2013.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Carbon aerogels are composed of particles with sizes in the nanometer range, covalently bonded together.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] They have very high porosity (over 50%, with pore diameter under 100 nm) and surface areas ranging between 400 and 1,000 m2/g.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] They are often manufactured as composite paper: non-woven paper made of carbon fibers, impregnated with resorcinol–formaldehyde aerogel, and pyrolyzed.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Depending on the density, carbon aerogels may be electrically conductive, making composite aerogel paper useful for electrodes in capacitors or deionization electrodes.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Due to their extremely high surface area, carbon aerogels are used to create supercapacitors, with values ranging up to thousands of farads based on a capacitance density of 104 F/g and 77 F/cm3.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Carbon aerogels are also extremely "black" in the infrared spectrum, reflecting only 0.3% of radiation between 250 nm and 14.3 μm, making them efficient for solar energy collectors.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] The term "aerogel" to describe airy masses of carbon nanotubes produced through certain chemical vapor deposition techniques is incorrect.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Such materials can be spun into fibers with strength greater than Kevlar, and unique electrical properties.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] These materials are not aerogels, however, since they do not have a monolithic internal structure and do not have the regular pore structure characteristic of aerogels.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Metal oxide aerogels are used as catalysts in various chemical reactions/transformations or as precursors for other materials.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogels made with aluminium oxide are known as alumina aerogels.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] These aerogels are used as catalysts, especially when "doped" with a metal other than aluminium.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Nickel–alumina aerogel is the most common combination.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Alumina aerogels are also being considered by NASA for capturing hypervelocity particles; a formulation doped with gadolinium and terbium could fluoresce at the particle impact site, with the amount of fluorescence dependent on impact energy.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] One of the most notable differences between silica aerogels and metal oxide aerogel is that metal oxide aerogels are often variedly colored.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Organic polymers can be used to create aerogels.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Cellulose from plants can be used to create a flexible aerogel.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] GraPhage13 is the first graphene-based aerogel assembled using graphene oxide and the M13 bacteriophage.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Chalcogel is an aerogel made of chalcogens (the column of elements on the periodic table beginning with oxygen) such as sulfur, selenium, and other elements.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Metals less expensive than platinum have been used in its creation.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogels made of cadmium selenide quantum dots in a porous 3-D network have been developed for use in the semiconductor industry.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogel performance may be augmented for a specific application by the addition of dopants, reinforcing structures, and hybridizing compounds.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] For example, Spaceloft is a composite of aerogel with some kind of fibrous batting.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Amyloid fibrils from food waste (whey) have the potential for use in AF aerogels for gold extraction from e-waste.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Their use would have a less environmental impact than that of the conventional use of activated carbon as adsorbent.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Aerogels are used in a wide range of applications because of their low density, low thermal conductivity, and high surface area.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Silica aerogels were the first to be developed commercially and remain the most widely used type.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Flexible polymer-based aerogels have been developed to overcome the brittleness of traditional silica aerogels and enable thin, mechanically compliant insulating materials for aerospace and electronic systems.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Polyimide aerogel films derived from NASA-developed aerogel technology have been commercialized for such applications; examples include the polyimide aerogel film *AeroZero*.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Silica-based aerogels are not known to be carcinogenic or toxic.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] However, they are a mechanical irritant to the eyes, skin, respiratory tract, and digestive system.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] They can also induce dryness of the skin, eyes, and mucous membranes.
[src:ice-protection-system/aerogel] Therefore, it is recommended that protective gear including respiratory protection, gloves and eye goggles be worn whenever handling or processing bare aerogels, particularly when a dust or fine fragments may occur.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] A significant part of **aeronautical science** is a branch of dynamics called aerodynamics, which deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Attempts to fly without any real aeronautical understanding have been made from the earliest times, typically by constructing wings and jumping from a tower with crippling or lethal results.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Wiser investigators sought to gain some rational understanding through the study of bird flight.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Medieval Islamic Golden Age scientists such as Abbas ibn Firnas also made such studies.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] The founders of modern aeronautics, Leonardo da Vinci in the Renaissance and Cayley in 1799, both began their investigations with studies of bird flight.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Man-carrying kites are believed to have been used extensively in ancient China.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] In 1282 the Italian explorer Marco Polo described the Chinese techniques then current.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] The Chinese also constructed small hot air balloons, or lanterns, and rotary-wing toys.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] An early European to provide any scientific discussion of flight was Roger Bacon, who described principles of operation for the lighter-than-air balloon and the flapping-wing ornithopter, which he envisaged would be constructed in the future.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] The lifting medium for his balloon would be an "aether" whose composition he did not know.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] In the late fifteenth century, Leonardo da Vinci followed up his study of birds with designs for some of the earliest flying machines, including the flapping-wing ornithopter and the rotating-wing helicopter.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Although his designs were rational, they were not based on particularly good science.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Many of his designs, such as a four-person screw-type helicopter, have severe flaws.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Da Vinci's work was lost after his death and did not reappear until it had been overtaken by the work of George Cayley.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] The modern era of lighter-than-air flight began early in the 17th century with Galileo's experiments in which he showed that air has weight.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Around 1650 Cyrano de Bergerac wrote some fantasy novels in which he described the principle of ascent using a substance (dew) he supposed to be lighter than air, and descending by releasing a controlled amount of the substance.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Francesco Lana de Terzi measured the pressure of air at sea level and in 1670 proposed the first scientifically credible lifting medium in the form of hollow metal spheres from which all the air had been pumped out.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] These would be lighter than the displaced air and able to lift an airship.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] His proposed methods of controlling height are still in use today; by carrying ballast which may be dropped overboard to gain height, and by venting the lifting containers to lose height.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] In practice de Terzi's spheres would have collapsed under air pressure, and further developments had to wait for more practicable lifting gases.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] From the mid-18th century the Montgolfier brothers in France began experimenting with balloons.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Their balloons were made of paper, and early experiments using steam as the lifting gas were short-lived due to its effect on the paper as it condensed.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Meanwhile, the discovery of hydrogen led Joseph Black in c.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] 1780 to propose its use as a lifting gas, though practical demonstration awaited a gas-tight balloon material.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] On hearing of the Montgolfier Brothers' invitation, the French Academy member Jacques Charles offered a similar demonstration of a hydrogen balloon.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Charles and two craftsmen, the Robert brothers, developed a gas-tight material of rubberised silk for the envelope.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] The hydrogen gas was to be generated by chemical reaction during the filling process.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] The Montgolfier designs had several shortcomings, not least the need for dry weather and a tendency for sparks from the fire to set light to the paper balloon.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] The manned design had a gallery around the base of the balloon rather than the hanging basket of the first, unmanned design, which brought the paper closer to the fire.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] On their free flight, De Rozier and d'Arlandes took buckets of water and sponges to douse these fires as they arose.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] On the other hand, the manned design of Charles was essentially modern.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] As a result of these exploits, the hot air balloon became known as the *Montgolfière* type and the gas balloon the *Charlière*.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Charles and the Robert brothers' next balloon, *La Caroline*, was a Charlière that followed Jean Baptiste Meusnier's proposals for an elongated dirigible balloon, and was notable for having an outer envelope with the gas contained in a second, inner ballonet.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] On 19 September 1784, it completed the first flight of over 100 kilometres (62 mi), between Paris and Beuvry, despite the man-powered propulsive devices proving useless.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] The balloon envelope was made of goldbeater's skin.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] The first flight ended in disaster and the approach has seldom been used since.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Sir George Cayley (1773–1857) is widely acknowledged as the founder of modern aeronautics.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] He was first called the "father of the aeroplane" in 1846 and Henson called him the "father of aerial navigation." He was the first true scientific aerial investigator to publish his work, which included for the first time the underlying principles and forces of flight.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] In 1809 he began the publication of a landmark three-part treatise titled "On Aerial Navigation" (1809–1810).
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] He developed the modern conventional form of the fixed-wing aeroplane having a stabilising tail with both horizontal and vertical surfaces, flying gliders both unmanned and manned.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] He introduced the use of the whirling arm test rig to investigate the aerodynamics of flight, using it to discover the benefits of the curved or cambered aerofoil over the flat wing he had used for his first glider.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] He also identified and described the importance of dihedral, diagonal bracing and drag reduction, and contributed to the understanding and design of ornithopters and parachutes.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Another significant invention was the tension-spoked wheel, which he devised in order to create a light, strong wheel for aircraft undercarriage.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] During the 19th century, Cayley's ideas were further developed, tested, and formalised.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Public and scientific interest in aeronautics grew during the Victorian era, with notable contributions from figures such as John Stringfellow, James Glaisher, Francis Wenham, and Frederick Brearey.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Wenham, Glaisher, and Brearey co-founded the Aeronautical Society of Great Britain in 1866, together with the 8th Duke of Argyll.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Although aeronautical research at the time remained largely experimental, the Society played an important role in promoting heavier-than-air flight, including through the First Aeronautical Exhibition held in 1868 at The Crystal Palace.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] These developments, along with growing international interest, helped lay the groundwork for the later work of Horatio Phillips among others, but more importantly of Otto Lilienthal, a German engineer and businessman who became known as the "flying man".
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] He was the first person to make well-documented, repeated, successful flights with gliders, therefore making the idea of "heavier than air" a reality.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Newspapers and magazines published photographs of Lilienthal gliding, favourably influencing public and scientific opinion about the possibility of flying machines becoming practical.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] His work led to the development of the modern wing.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] His flight attempts in Berlin in the year 1891 are seen as the beginning of human flight and the "Lilienthal Normalsegelapparat" is considered to be the first air plane in series production, making the *Maschinenfabrik Otto Lilienthal* in Berlin the first air plane production company in the world.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Otto Lilienthal is often referred to as either the "father of aviation" or "father of flight".
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Aeronautics may be divided into three main branches, Aviation, Aeronautical science and Aeronautical engineering.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Aviation is the art or practice of aeronautics.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Historically aviation meant only heavier-than-air flight, but nowadays it includes flying in balloons and airships.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Aeronautical engineering covers the design and construction of aircraft, including how they are powered, how they are used and how they are controlled for safe operation.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] A major part of aeronautical engineering is aerodynamics, the science of passing through the air.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] With the increasing activity in space flight, nowadays aeronautics and astronautics are often combined as aerospace engineering.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] The science of aerodynamics deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] A rocket or rocket vehicle is a missile, spacecraft, aircraft or other vehicle which obtains thrust from a rocket engine.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] In all rockets, the exhaust is formed entirely from propellants carried within the rocket before use.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Rocket engines work by action and reaction.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Rocket engines push rockets forwards simply by throwing their exhaust backwards extremely fast.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Rockets for military and recreational uses date back to at least 13th-century China.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Significant scientific, interplanetary and industrial use did not occur until the 20th century, when rocketry was the enabling technology of the Space Age, including setting foot on the Moon.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Rockets are used for fireworks, weaponry, ejection seats, launch vehicles for artificial satellites, human spaceflight and exploration of other planets.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] While comparatively inefficient for low speed use, they are very lightweight and powerful, capable of generating large accelerations and of attaining extremely high speeds with reasonable efficiency.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Chemical rockets are the most common type of rocket and they typically create their exhaust by the combustion of rocket propellant.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] Chemical rockets store a large amount of energy in an easily released form, and can be very dangerous.
[src:ice-protection-system/aeronautics] However, careful design, testing, construction and use minimizes risks.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The **aft pressure bulkhead** or **rear pressure bulkhead** is the rear component of the pressure seal in all aircraft that cruise in a tropopause zone in the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] It helps maintain pressure when stratocruising and protects the aircraft from bursting due to the higher internal pressure.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Aft pressure bulkheads can either be curved, which reduces the amount of metal needed at the cost of reducing the usable space in the airliner, or flat, which gives more internal space but also more weight.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Patents have been filed that propose deliberately creating cavities within the rear bulkhead with the purpose of providing more usable cabin space.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] On several airliners, production of the rear pressure bulkhead has been outsourced to third party manufacturers.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] While typically being a time-consuming and somewhat uncommon process, an aircraft's aft pressure bulkhead can be wholly replaced.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During the twenty-first century, various parties became increasingly interested in developing aft pressure bulkheads composed from composite materials, seeking benefits such as lower manufacturing costs, easier sealing, elimination of corrosion risk, along with weight and part count reductions.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During the early 2000s, Airbus Group developed the largest manufactured resin film infusion structure then in production to function as the aft pressure bulkhead for their double-decker A380 airliner.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Multiple instances of damage to the aft pressure bulkhead have occurred; while a few cases have led to serious failures leading to aircraft losses, others have proven to be survivable.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Aviation certifying authorities have often mandated inspections of an aircraft's aft pressure bulkhead in the interest of safety.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Various techniques have been devised to determine the integrity of the rear pressure bulkhead; these have been used not only to inspect in-service examples but also in the design process, helping to design efficient bulkheads that possess sufficient strength to ensure a safe operational life.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] In 1971, British European Airways Flight 706 crashed in Belgium, killing all 63 on board; the cause was determined to be corrosion of the rear pressure bulkhead by fluid contamination, perhaps from the lavatory.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The corrosion was not detectable by the inspection techniques at the time.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] In 1985, Japan Air Lines Flight 123 crashed after a catastrophic failure of the aft pressure bulkhead.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The failure occurred due to faulty repair of the bulkhead after a tailstrike seven years earlier, when a single repair patch plate was incorrectly cut in two "to make it fit".
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Failure of the bulkhead damaged hydraulic pipes passing through.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Boeing later calculated that the incorrect installation would be expected to fail after approximately 10,000 pressurizations; the repaired aircraft accomplished 12,318 successful flights before the crash.
[src:ice-protection-system/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During 2013, National Airlines Flight 102 crashed after loose freight on the main deck is believed to have penetrated the aft pressure bulkhead and caused damage to control systems in the vicinity of the bulkhead.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] An **aileron** (French for 'little wing' or 'fin') is a hinged flight control surface usually forming part of the trailing edge of each wing of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Ailerons are used in pairs to control the aircraft in roll (or movement around the aircraft's longitudinal axis), which normally results in a change in flight path due to the tilting of the lift vector.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Movement around this axis is called rolling or banking.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Considerable controversy exists over credit for the invention of the aileron.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The Wright brothers and Glenn Curtiss fought a years-long legal battle over the Wright patent of 1906, which described a method of wing-warping to achieve lateral control.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The brothers prevailed in several court decisions which found that Curtiss's use of ailerons violated the Wright patent.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Ultimately, the First World War compelled the U.S.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Government to legislate a legal resolution.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] A much earlier aileron concept was patented in 1868 by British scientist Matthew Piers Watt Boulton, based on his 1864 paper *On Aërial Locomotion*.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The name "aileron", from French, meaning "little wing", also refers to the extremities of a bird's wings used to control their flight.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] It first appeared in print in the 7th edition of Cassell's French-English Dictionary of 1877, with its lead meaning of "small wing".
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] In the context of powered airplanes it appears in print about 1908.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Prior to that, ailerons were often referred to as rudders, their older technical sibling, with no distinction between their orientations and functions, or more descriptively as *horizontal rudders* (in French, *gouvernails horizontaux*).
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Among the earliest printed aeronautical use of 'aileron' was that in the French aviation journal *L'Aérophile* of 1908.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Ailerons had more or less completely supplanted other forms of lateral control, such as wing warping, by about 1915, well after the function of the rudder and elevator flight controls had been largely standardised.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] He was the first to patent an aileron control system in 1868.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Boulton's description of his lateral flight control system was "the first record we have of appreciation of the necessity for active lateral control as distinguished from [passive lateral stability]....
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] With this invention of Boulton's we have the birth of the present-day three torque method of airborne control" as was praised by Charles Manly.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] 392 of 1868, issued about 35 years before ailerons were "reinvented" in France, became forgotten and lost from sight until after the flight control device was in general use.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Gibbs-Smith stated on several occasions that if the Boulton patent had been revealed at the time of the Wright brothers' legal filings, they might not have been able to claim priority of invention for the lateral control of flying machines.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The fact that the Wright brothers were able to gain a patent in 1906 did not invalidate Boulton's lost and forgotten invention.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The pioneering U.S. aeronautical engineer Octave Chanute published descriptions and drawings of the Wright brothers' 1902 glider in the leading aviation periodical of the day, *L'Aérophile*, in 1903.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] This prompted Esnault-Pelterie, a French military engineer, to build a Wright-style glider in 1904 that used ailerons in lieu of wing warping.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The French journal *L'Aérophile* then published photos of the ailerons on Esnault-Pelterie's glider which were included in his June 1905 article, and its ailerons were widely copied afterward.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The Wright brothers used wing warping instead of ailerons for roll control on their glider in 1902, and about 1904 their Flyer II was the only aircraft of its time able to do a coordinated banked turn.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] During the early years of powered flight the Wrights had better roll control on their designs than airplanes that used movable surfaces.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] From 1908, as aileron designs were refined it became clear that ailerons were much more effective and practical than wing warping.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Ailerons also had the advantage of not weakening the airplane's wing structure as did the wing warping technique, which was one reason for Esnault-Pelterie's decision to switch to ailerons.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] By 1911, most biplanes used ailerons rather than wing warping—by 1915, ailerons had become almost universal on monoplanes as well.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Government, frustrated by the lack of its country's aeronautical advances in the years leading up to World War I, enforced a patent pool effectively putting an end to the Wright brothers patent war.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The Wright company quietly changed its aircraft flight controls from wing warping to the use of ailerons at that time as well.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The Wright Brothers' Ohio patent attorney Henry Toulmin filed an expansive patent application and on May 22, 1906, the brothers were granted U.S.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The patent's importance lay in its claim of a new and useful method of *controlling* an airplane.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The patent application included the claim for the lateral control of aircraft flight that was not limited to wing warping, but through any manipulation of the "....angular relations of the lateral margins of the airplanes [wings].... varied in opposite directions".
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Thus the patent explicitly stated that other methods besides wing-warping could be used for adjusting the outer portions of an airplane's wings to different angles on its right and left sides to achieve lateral roll control.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Patent 831173 at nearly the same time for his methods of wing warping.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Both the Wright Brothers patent and Montgomery's patent were reviewed and approved by the same patent examiner at the United States Patent Office, William Townsend.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] At the time Townsend indicated that both methods of wing warping were invented independently and were sufficiently different to each justify their own patent award.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Multiple U.S. court decisions favoured the expansive Wright patent, which the Wright Brothers sought to enforce with licensing fees starting from $1,000 per airplane, and said to range up to $1,000 per day.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Casey, a former curator of the Smithsonian Air & Space Museum in Washington, D.C., and other researchers, due to the patent they had received the Wrights stood firmly on the position that all flying using lateral roll control, anywhere in the world, would only be conducted under license by them.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Years of protracted legal conflict ensued with many other aircraft builders until the U.S. entered World War I, when the government imposed a legislated agreement among the parties which resulted in royalty payments of 1% to the Wrights.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] There are still conflicting claims today over who first invented the aileron.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Other 19th century engineers and scientists, including Charles Renard, Alphonse Pénaud, and Louis Mouillard, had described similar flight control surfaces.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Another technique for lateral flight control, wing warping, was also described or experimented with by several people including Jean-Marie Le Bris, John Montgomery, Clement Ader, Edson Gallaudet, D.D.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Gibbs-Smith wrote that the aileron was "....one of the most remarkable inventions... of aeronautical history, which was immediately lost sight of".
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Ailerons are usually situated near the wing tip, but may sometimes also be situated nearer the wing root.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Modern airliners may also have a second pair of ailerons on their wings, with the two positions distinguished by the terms "outboard aileron" and "inboard aileron".
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] An unwanted side effect of aileron operation is adverse yaw, a yawing moment in the opposite direction to the roll.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Using the ailerons to roll an aircraft to the right produces a yawing motion to the left.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] As the aircraft rolls, adverse yaw is caused partly by the change in drag between the left and right wing.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The rising wing generates increased lift, which causes increased induced drag.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The descending wing generates reduced lift, which causes reduced induced drag.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Profile drag caused by the deflected ailerons may add further to the difference, along with changes in the lift vectors as one rotates back while the other rotates forward.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] In a coordinated turn, adverse yaw is effectively compensated by the use of the rudder, which results in a sideforce on the vertical tail that opposes the adverse yaw by creating a favorable yawing moment.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Another method of compensation is "differential ailerons", which have been rigged so that the down-going aileron deflects less than the up-going one.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] In this case the opposing yaw moment is generated by a difference in profile drag between the left and right wingtips.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Ailerons may also be designed to use a combination of these methods.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] With ailerons in the neutral position, the wing on the outside of the turn develops more lift than the opposite wing due to the variation in airspeed across the wing span, which tends to cause the aircraft to continue to roll.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Once the desired angle of bank (degree of rotation about the longitudinal axis) has been obtained, the pilot uses opposite aileron to prevent the angle of bank from increasing due to this variation in lift across the wing span.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] This minor opposite use of the control must be maintained throughout the turn.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The pilot also uses a slight amount of rudder in the same direction as the turn to counteract adverse yaw and to produce a "coordinated" turn wherein the fuselage is parallel to the flight path.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] A simple gauge on the instrument panel called the slip indicator, also known as "the ball", indicates when this coordination is achieved.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Particularly on larger or faster aircraft, control forces may be extremely heavy.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Borrowing a discovery from boats that extending a control surface's area forward of the hinge lightens the forces needed first appeared on ailerons during World War I when ailerons were extended beyond the wingtip and provided with a horn ahead of the hinge.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Known as overhung ailerons, possibly the best known examples are the Handley Page Type O (first flight 17 December 1915), Sopwith Snipe, Fokker Dr.I and Fokker D.VII.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Later examples brought the counterbalance in line with the wing to improve control and reduce drag.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] This is seen less often now, due to the Frise type aileron which provides the same benefit.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Trim tabs are small movable sections resembling scaled down ailerons located at or near the trailing edge of the aileron.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] On most propeller powered aircraft, the rotation of the propellers induces a counteracting roll movement due to Newton's third law of motion, in that every action has an equal and opposite reaction.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] To relieve the pilot of having to provide continuous pressure on the stick in one direction, which causes fatigue, trim tabs are provided to adjust or *trim out* the pressure needed against any unwanted movement.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The tab itself is deflected in relation to the aileron, causing the aileron to move in the opposite direction.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Trim tabs come in two forms, adjustable and fixed.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] A fixed trim tab is manually bent to the required amount of deflection, while the adjustable trim tab can be controlled from within the cockpit so that different power settings or flight attitudes can be compensated for.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Some large aircraft from the 1950s (including the Canadair Argus) used free floating control surfaces that the pilot controlled only through the deflection of trim tabs, in which case additional tabs were also provided to fine-tune the control to provide straight and level flight.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Spades are flat metal plates, usually attached to the aileron lower surface, ahead of the aileron hinge, by a lever arm.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] They reduce the force needed by the pilot to deflect the aileron and are often seen on aerobatic aircraft.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] As the aileron is deflected upward, the spade produces a downward aerodynamic force, which tends to rotate the whole assembly so as to further deflect the aileron upward.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The size of the spade (and its lever arm) determines how much force the pilot needs to apply to deflect the aileron.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] A spade works in the same manner as a horn but is more effective due to the longer moment arm.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] To increase the speed at which control surface flutter (aeroelastic flutter) might become a risk, the center of gravity of the control surface is moved towards the hinge-line for that surface.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] To achieve this, lead weights may be added to the front of the aileron.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] In some aircraft the aileron construction may be too heavy to allow this system to work without an excessive increase in the weight of the aileron.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] In this case, the weight may be added to a lever arm to move the weight well out in front to the aileron body.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] These balance weights are tear drop shaped (to reduce drag), which make them appear quite different from spades, although both project forward and below the aileron.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] In addition to reducing the risk of flutter, mass balances also reduce the stick forces required to move the control surface in maneuvers.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Used during aviation's pre-war "pioneer era" and into the early years of the First World War, these ailerons were each controlled by a single cable, which pulled the aileron up.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] When the aircraft was at rest, the ailerons hung vertically down.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] This type of aileron was used on the Farman III biplane 1909 and the Short 166.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] A "reverse" version of this, utilizing wing-warping, existed on the later version of the Santos-Dumont *Demoiselle*, which only warped the wingtips "downward".
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] One of the disadvantages of this setup was a greater tendency to yaw than even with basic interconnected ailerons.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] During the 1930s, a number of light aircraft used single acting controls but used springs to return the ailerons to their neutral positions when the stick was released.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The main problem with this type of aileron is the dangerous tendency to stall if used aggressively, especially if the aircraft is already in danger of stalling, hence the use primarily on prototypes, and their replacement on production aircraft with more conventional ailerons.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Engineer Leslie George Frise (1897–1979) of the Bristol Aeroplane Company developed an aileron shape that is pivoted at about its 25 to 30% chord line and near its bottom surface , in order to decrease stick forces as aircraft became faster during the 1930s.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] When the aileron is deflected up (to make its wing go down), the leading edge of the aileron starts to protrude below the underside of the wing into the airflow beneath the wing.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The moment of the leading edge in the airflow helps to move up the trailing edge, which decreases the stick force.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The down moving aileron also adds energy to the boundary layer.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The edge of the aileron directs air flow from the underside of the wing to the upper surface of the aileron, thus creating a lifting force added to the lift of the wing.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] This reduces the needed deflection of the aileron.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Both the Canadian Fleet Model 2 biplane of 1930 and the 1938 popular US Piper J-3 Cub monoplane possessed Frise ailerons as designed and helped introduce them to a wide audience.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] A claimed benefit of the Frise aileron is the ability to counteract adverse yaw.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] To do so, the leading edge of the aileron has to be sharp or bluntly rounded, which adds significant drag to the upturned aileron and helps counterbalance the yaw force created by the other aileron turned down.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] This can add some unpleasant, nonlinear effect and/or potentially dangerous aerodynamic vibration (flutter).
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Adverse yaw moment is basically countered by aircraft yaw stability and also by the use of differential aileron movement.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The Frise-type aileron also forms a slot, so air flows smoothly over the lowered aileron, making it more effective at high angles of attack.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Frise-type ailerons may also be designed to function differentially.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Like the differential aileron, the Frise-type aileron does not eliminate adverse yaw entirely.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Coordinated rudder application is still needed when ailerons are applied.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] By careful design of the mechanical linkages, the up aileron can be made to deflect more than the down aileron (e.g., US patent 1,565,097).
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] This helps reduce the likelihood of a wing tip stall when aileron deflections are made at high angles of attack.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] In addition, the consequent differential in drag reduces adverse yaw (as also discussed above).
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The idea is that the loss of lift associated with the up aileron carries no penalty while the increase in lift associated with the down aileron is minimized.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The rolling couple on the aircraft is always the difference in lift between the two wings.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] A designer at de Havilland invented a simple and practical linkage and their de Havilland Tiger Moth classic British biplane became one of the best-known aircraft, and one of the earliest, to use differential ailerons.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] On the earliest Pioneer Era aircraft, such as the Wright Flyer and the later, 1909-origin Blériot XI and Etrich Taube, lateral control was effected by twisting the outboard portion of the wing so as to increase or decrease lift by changing the angle of attack.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] This had the disadvantages of stressing the structure, being heavy on the controls, and of risking stalling the side with the increased angle of attack during a maneuver.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] By 1916, most designers had abandoned wing warping in favor of ailerons.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Researchers at NASA and elsewhere have been taking a second look at wing warping again, although under new names.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The NASA version is the X-53 Active Aeroelastic Wing while the United States Air Force tested the Adaptive Compliant Wing.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Spoilers are devices that when extended into the airflow over a wing, disrupt the airflow and reduce the amount of lift generated.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Many modern aircraft designs, especially jet aircraft, use spoilers in lieu of, or to supplement ailerons, such as the F4 Phantom II and Northrop P-61 Black Widow, which had almost full width flaps (there were very small conventional ailerons at the wingtips as well).
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] All aircraft with dihedral have some form of yaw-roll coupling to promote stability.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Common trainers like the Cessna 152/172 series can be roll controlled with rudder alone.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] The rudder of the Boeing 737 has more roll authority over the aircraft than the ailerons at high angles of attack.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] This led to two notable accidents when the rudder jammed in the fully deflected position causing rollovers (see Boeing 737 rudder issues).
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Some aircraft such as the Fokker Spin and model gliders lack any type of lateral control.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Those aircraft use a higher amount of dihedral than conventional aircraft.
[src:ice-protection-system/aileron] Deflecting the rudder gives yaw and a lot of differential wing lift, giving a yaw induced roll moment.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] In aeronautics, **ice protection systems** keep atmospheric moisture from accumulating on aircraft surfaces, such as wings, propellers, rotor blades, engine intakes, and environmental control intakes.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Ice buildup can change the shape of airfoils and flight control surfaces, degrading control and handling characteristics as well as performance.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] An anti-icing, de-icing, or ice protection system either prevents formation of ice, or enables the aircraft to shed the ice before it becomes dangerous.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Aircraft icing increases weight and drag, decreases lift, and can decrease thrust.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Ice reduces engine power by blocking air intakes.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] When ice builds up by freezing upon impact or freezing as runoff, it changes the aerodynamics of the surface by modifying the shape and the smoothness of the surface which increases drag, and decreases wing lift or propeller thrust.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Both a decrease in lift on the wing due to an altered airfoil shape, and the increase in weight from the ice load will usually result having to fly at a greater angle of attack to compensate for lost lift to maintain altitude.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] This increases fuel consumption and further reduces speed, making a stall more likely to occur, causing the aircraft to lose altitude.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Ice accumulates on helicopter rotor blades and aircraft propellers causing weight and aerodynamic imbalances that are amplified due to their rotation.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Anti-ice systems installed on jet engines or turboprops help prevent airflow problems and avert the risk of serious internal engine damage from ingested ice.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] These concerns are most acute with turboprops, which more often have sharp turns in the intake path where ice tends to accumulate.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] The pneumatic boot is usually made of layers of rubber or other elastomers, with one or more air chambers between the layers.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] If multiple chambers are used, they are typically shaped as stripes aligned with the long direction of the boot.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] It is typically placed on the leading edge of an aircraft's wings and stabilizers.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] The chambers are rapidly inflated and deflated, either simultaneously, or in a pattern of specific chambers only.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] The rapid change in shape of the boot is designed to break the adhesive force between the ice and the rubber, and allow the ice to be carried away by the air flowing past the wing.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] However, the ice must fall away cleanly from the trailing sections of the surface, or it could re-freeze behind the protected area.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Re-freezing of ice in this manner was a contributing factor to the crash of American Eagle Flight 4184.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Older pneumatic boots were thought to be subject to ice bridging.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Slush could be pushed out of reach of the inflatable sections of the boot before hardening.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] This was resolved by speeding up the inflation/deflation cycle, and by alternating the timing of adjacent cells.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Testing and case studies performed in the 1990s have demonstrated that ice bridging is not a significant concern with modern boot designs.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Pneumatic boots are appropriate for low and medium speed aircraft, without leading edge lift devices such as slats, so this system is most commonly found on smaller turboprop aircraft such as the Saab 340 and Embraer EMB 120 Brasilia.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Pneumatic de-icing boots are sometimes found on other types, especially older aircraft.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] These are rarely used on modern jet aircraft.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Sometimes called a weeping wing, running wet, or evaporative system, these systems use a deicing fluid, typically based on ethylene glycol or isopropyl alcohol, to prevent ice forming and to break up accumulated ice on critical surfaces of an aircraft.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] One or two electrically-driven pumps send the fluid to proportioning units that divide the flow between areas to be protected.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] A second pump is used for redundancy, especially for aircraft certified for flight into known icing conditions, with additional mechanical pumps for the windshield.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Fluid is forced through holes in panels on the leading edges of the wings, horizontal stabilizers, fairings, struts, engine inlets, and from a slinger-ring on the propeller and the windshield sprayer.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] These panels have 1⁄400 inch (0.064 mm) diameter holes drilled in them, with 800 holes per square inch (120/cm2).
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] The system is self cleaning, and the fluid helps clean the aircraft, before it is blown away by the slipstream.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] The system was initially used during World War II by the British, having been developed by Tecalemit-Kilfrost-Sheepbridge Stokes (TKS).
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Advantages of fluid systems are mechanical simplicity and minimal airflow disruption from the minuscule holes; this made the systems popular in older business jets.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Disadvantages are greater maintenance requirements than pneumatic boots, the weight of potentially unneeded fluid aboard the aircraft, the finite supply of fluid when it is needed, and the unpredictable need to refill the fluid, which complicates en route stops.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Bleed air systems are used by most large aircraft with jet engines or turboprops.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Hot air is "bled" off one or more engines' compressor sections into tubes routed through wings, tail surfaces, and engine inlets.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Spent air is exhausted through holes in the wings' undersides.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] A disadvantage of these systems is that supplying an adequate amount of bleed air can negatively affect engine performance.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Higher-than-normal power settings are often required during cruise or descent, particularly with one or more inoperative engines.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] More significantly, use of bleed air affects engine temperature limits and often necessitates reduced power settings during climb, which may cause a substantial loss of climb performance with particularly critical consequences if an engine were to fail.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] This latter concern has resulted in bleed air systems being uncommon in small turbine aircraft, although they have been successfully implemented on some small aircraft such as the Cessna CitationJet.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Electro-thermal systems use heating coils (much like a low output stove element) buried in the airframe structure to generate heat when a current is applied.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] The heat can be generated continuously, or intermittently.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] The Boeing 787 Dreamliner uses electro-thermal ice protection.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] In this case the heating coils are embedded within the composite wing structure.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Boeing claims the system uses half the energy of engine fed bleed-air systems, and reduces drag and noise.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Etched foil heating coils can be bonded to the inside of metal aircraft skins to lower power use compared to embedded circuits as they operate at higher power densities.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] For general aviation, ThermaWing uses a flexible, electrically conductive, graphite foil attached to a wing's leading edge.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Electric heaters heat the foil which melts ice.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Small wires or other conductive materials can be embedded in the windscreen to heat the windscreen.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Pilots can turn on the electric heater to provide sufficient heat to prevent the formation of ice on the windscreen.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] However, windscreen electric heaters may only be used in flight, as they can overheat the windscreen.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] They can also cause compass deviation errors by as much as 40°.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] One proposal used carbon nanotubes formed into thin filaments which are spun into a 10 micron-thick film.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] The film is a poor electrical conductor, due to gaps between the nanotubes.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Instead, current causes a rapid rise in temperature, heating up twice as fast as nichrome, the heating element of choice for in-flight de-icing, while using half the energy at one ten-thousandth the weight.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Sufficient material to cover the wings of a 747 weighs 80 g (2.8 oz) and costs roughly 1% of nichrome.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Aerogel heaters have also been suggested, which could be left on continuously at low power.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Electro-mechanical expulsion deicing systems (EMEDS) use a percussive force initiated by actuators inside the structure which induce a shock wave in the surface to be cleared.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Hybrid systems have also been developed that combine the EMEDS with heating elements, where a heater prevents ice accumulation on the leading edge of the airfoil and the EMED system removes accumulations aft of the heated portion of the airfoil.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Passive systems employ icephobic surfaces.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Icephobicity is analogous to hydrophobicity and describes a material property that is resistant to icing.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] The term is not well defined but generally includes three properties: low adhesion between ice and the surface, prevention of ice formation, and a repellent effect on supercooled droplets.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Icephobicity requires special material properties but is not identical to hydrophobicity.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] To minimize accretion, researchers are seeking icephobic materials.
[src:ice-protection-system/ice-protection-system] Candidates include carbon nanotubes and slippery liquid infused porous surfaces (SLIPS) which repel water when it forms into ice.
